  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Ceiling height is one of those property features that buyers often respond to without consciously realising why. A taller room feels lighter, more generous, and more expensive than its floor area would suggest. A lower room feels practical but ordinary, even when the finishes are identical. In Brisbane, where the heritage Queenslander stock includes some of the most generously proportioned interiors in any Australian city, ceiling height is a feature that meaningfully separates the most desirable homes from the merely competent ones. Sellers who understand how buyers read ceiling height, what to call attention to in marketing, and how to stage for height produce stronger results without spending heavily on the property itself.</p>

      <p>This article walks through what the standard ceiling height is, what counts as elevated, why height drives perception of value, the heritage Queenslander advantage, and how to stage and market a home for the height it has.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The standard ceiling height</h2>
      <p>Modern Australian residential builds use 2.4 metres as the standard ceiling height. This is the legal minimum under the National Construction Code for habitable rooms. Most post-1970 Brisbane homes have 2.4 metre ceilings throughout. This is the default that most buyers are subconsciously calibrated to, which means that anything above 2.4 metres registers as a positive feature, often disproportionately to the small absolute increase in height.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What extra height looks like in Brisbane</h2>
      <p>Above the standard, the typical brackets are 2.55 to 2.7 metres, common in mid-to-upper tier new builds completed since 2000; 2.7 to 3.0 metres, typical of premium new builds and many heritage Queenslanders; and above 3.0 metres, generally restricted to grand pre-1947 Queenslanders, some heritage workers cottages with raised hipped ceilings, and apartment penthouses. Each of these brackets reads differently to buyers. The jump from 2.4 to 2.55 metres feels noticeable but not dramatic. The jump to 2.7 metres feels distinctly generous. Above 3 metres, the home reads as an architectural statement and the height becomes part of the property's identity.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why ceiling height matters more than buyers realise</h2>
      <p>The reasons height is so disproportionately powerful are mostly perceptual. Higher ceilings make rooms feel larger without increasing the footprint, and the brain reads volume as much as floor area when judging space. Higher ceilings allow for more and taller windows, which means more natural light, which is itself a major perceived-quality signal. Higher ceilings accommodate larger artwork, taller furniture, and pendant lighting, all of which signal a more considered interior. They signal a quality build to buyers even when other features are similar to a competing property, because most volume-built homes use the 2.4 metre standard and buyers (often correctly) read above-standard height as a marker of greater investment in the build.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The heritage Queenslander advantage</h2>
      <p>Many pre-1947 Queenslanders were built with ceilings in the 2.7 to 3.3 metre range, sometimes higher in the formal rooms. This was a climatic decision (taller rooms with cross-ventilation were the air conditioning of the day) but it has aged into one of the most valuable features of the heritage stock. The implications for sellers are significant. Do not lower these ceilings during renovation just to add insulation or to install ducted air conditioning, because the height is irreplaceable and the cost of reinstating it later is substantial. If a previous owner has dropped the ceiling for any reason, restoring the original height is one of the higher-return renovations available in a Queenslander, particularly in formal living and dining rooms.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The apartment context</h2>
      <p>Modern apartments at 2.55 to 2.7 metres are standard for the inner Brisbane market. Apartments above 3 metres are typically penthouse or premium category, and the ceiling height itself is usually a major part of the listing narrative. In apartments, ceiling height in the master bedroom is particularly valued because the buyer is expecting to spend the most time in that room and the perception of generosity matters most there. For mid-tier apartments at the standard 2.4 metre height, staging and styling become more important, because there is no structural advantage to lean on.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Staging for height</h2>
      <p>The staging principles for emphasising ceiling height are well established. Hang curtains close to the ceiling rather than just above the window frame, and let them fall to the floor. This vertical line draws the eye up and up, making the room feel taller. Use vertical-stripe wallpaper or wall paneling sparingly in feature locations to draw the eye up. Avoid heavy ceiling-mounted light fixtures that visually drop the ceiling, and prefer recessed downlights or pendant lighting hung at the appropriate height for the room scale. Use tall potted plants (figs, palms, kentia) in living rooms to introduce vertical interest. Hang artwork at the right scale: large pieces hung high look intentional in tall rooms and undersized pieces hung low make even tall rooms feel ordinary.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What not to do for staging</h2>
      <p>Do not paint the ceiling in a darker colour than the walls. Dark ceilings visually drop the ceiling height, which is exactly the opposite of what most sellers want. White or near-white ceilings continue to be the right choice in the great majority of rooms. Do not hang artwork too low, because eye-level positioning is the rule and undersized work hung at chest height makes a tall room feel awkward. Do not install bulkheads or dropped ceilings unless they are functionally necessary (typically for plumbing or electrical work above kitchens or bathrooms), and where they are necessary, design them to feel intentional rather than apologetic.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The photography angle</h2>
      <p>Professional real estate photographers use wider-angle lenses to capture ceiling height, but the result depends on shooting decisions as much as on equipment. Ensure the shoot includes vertical-format compositions that show the full ceiling-to-floor extent of generous rooms. Twilight and dusk shots emphasise pendant lighting and architectural ceiling features such as VJ boards, pressed metal, or exposed beams. Where ceiling height is unusual (above 2.55 metres), include the height as a written feature in the listing copy, because the photograph alone may not communicate the dimension to a viewer scrolling on a phone.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to mention in marketing</h2>
      <p>Specifics anchor buyer perception of quality far better than generic descriptors. "2.7 metre ceilings throughout", "soaring 3 metre ceilings", "high VJ ceilings" (for Queenslanders), "double-height void in the entry hall" all establish the dimension in the buyer's mind before they walk through the door. Where the home has a particularly distinctive ceiling feature (pressed metal, original ornate plaster cornices, exposed timber beams, restored ceiling roses) call them out by name. Specifics also help buyers calibrate the property against competing listings without relying on the photographs alone.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The renovation tradeoffs</h2>
      <p>Raising ceilings in a home that has standard 2.4 metre ceilings is structurally challenging and rarely worth the cost. It is typically only viable in single-storey homes with sufficient attic or roof-space depth, and even then the work is expensive once electrical, insulation, and finishes are considered. In Queenslanders that have had ceilings dropped at some point in their history, restoring the original ceiling height is a different proposition: the cavity already exists, the original cornice line is often preserved above the dropped ceiling, and the work tends to pay back well at sale. In any major renovation, treat existing ceiling height as a fixed asset and design around preserving it, not compromising it for ductwork or insulation that could be routed differently.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">A practical framework</h2>
      <p>Ceiling height is a fixed asset that cannot easily be added. If the home has it, market it actively, mention the dimensions in the listing, and stage to emphasise it. If it does not, focus on other features and use staging principles to maximise perception of space without overpromising. For buyers, ceiling height remains one of the strongest indirect signals of property quality, and sellers who treat it as a primary marketing asset rather than a footnote produce noticeably stronger results in the inner Brisbane market.</p>

